A fact we might find useful later is that there are 37 Wednesdays left before seniors graduate, including tonight. Given university breaks, about 29 of those Wednesdays will have active Woads. There are 29 Soads available as well, so there are a total of 58 potential nights-on-the-town.

Suppose you want to complete the 14-college challenge: hook up with one person in each of Yale's 14 residential colleges. Assume for simplicity that the probability of hooking up with someone in any given residential college is equal to the probability for any other residential college.
Let W be the number of times you must go to Woads or Soads & find a hook up in order to complete the 14-college challenge; E is the expectation function (here, the expected number of Woads/Toads nights until you complete your challenge). 

E(W) = E(H_1)+E(H_2)+...+E(H_14), 

where H_i is the event that you hook up with someone in a NEW residential college when you've already hooked up with people from i-1 residential colleges. Now E(H_i) is just the inverse of the probability of H_i on any given successful Woads/Soads (assume you always get exactly one hookup), so

E(H_i) = 1Ã·P(H_i) = 1Ã·((14-(i-1))Ã·14) = 14Ã·((15-i))

It follows that

E(W) = 1 + 14Ã·(13) + 14Ã·(12) + ... + 14
â‰ˆ 45.5

Moral of the story: hit every Woads and at least 17 Soads!

tl;dr find hookups 46 nights to expect to complete the 14-college challenge!

Notes from Meme-bridge Hall:

Dear Yale Meme Community,

We, the team, want to thank all of you for your undying support for and participation in Yaleâ€™s meme culture. Ever since that cold November day when Ephraim and I humbly founded this page, we have experienced incredible growth and success. 

Lately, a few other college meme groups, namely the Berkeley and Columbia ones, were approached by companies about the prospect of placing advertisements on their pages. We, too, have been contacted by startups and corporations alike about commercializing memes. To this day, we stand by the policy that succumbing to such a late-stage-capitalist tactic would spell a serious degradation in the creative process and very medium of memes. We were particularly offended by this practice since it seemed like the creators of those commercialized memes were merely pocketing the money for their own use, as opposed to considering ways in which the money raised could be given back to the community. 

Following this logic, it is with great pleasure that we announce Yale Memeâ€™s greatest plan yet: a guest speaker series featuring human memes funded with money from select advertisements. Bringing individuals such as Ken Bone or Jeb Bush on campus would be a great way to legitimize the bourgeoning online meme community around Yale, and to channel the capitalist construct of commercials into beneficial, non-profit use. We will keep these advertisement memes to a minimum, generating just enough to cover travel, room, and boarding costs for invited guest speakers. And, as with all memes, we will hold ourselves accountable to publishing only the best for this page. 

We hope youâ€™re as excited as we are for the future; we always remember that we are nothing without you, the constituents of the greatest meme community in American higher education. Thank you very much. 

Sincerely,

Charles Comiter and Ephraim Sutherland, Founders, Yale Memes for Special Snowflake Teens
